<subSubSection id="C6873230B5FEF59B4AD29EEB927BC142" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="way of life">
<paragraph id="0706C4074C691BE8A709141292C06999" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Way of life.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1DABD93087876B8A69C581A4662E668F" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Size range - 3.2 mm to 5.4 mm; these small beetles occur in Amazonian inundation forests of the Varzea and 
<normalizedToken id="9E161C8B9ABFCBB959BBACE37E845A22" originalValue="Igapó">Igapo</normalizedToken>
systems. Adults occur in very wet leaf litter and in rotten wood in swampy areas. One adult was found by insecticidal fogging of the suspended fronds of an 
<taxonomicName id="6408AA5B5791453F79A56919154F6E16" authorityName="G.F.W.Meyer" authorityYear="1818" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Astrocaryum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Arecales" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="114024C6B6BCFF2C7B93F9510B4C23EE" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Astrocaryum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
palm; no doubt it was seeking refuge from inundation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5BC5DE90829D1C4366C7846561E6D6D8" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="distribution">
